    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-03-05T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-03-05T02:00:00-05:00" n="352"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d352">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">852.24/551: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-03-05T08:00:00+01:00"
                            >March 5, 1938—8 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 9:15 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>91. In the <hi rend="italic">Angriff</hi>, the press organ of Minister Goebbels,
                    an alleged request of the Department to the “Red Spanish Embassy” to desist from
                    armament purchases in America was criticised as being merely intended to “save
                    face”. In a short editorial yesterday which concluded “that one will
                    nevertheless continue to make a profit—industry will simply negotiate direct—is
                    a neat proof of the skill of the Foreign Office of the United States. The arms
                    dealers will well know how to appreciate such skill.”</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
